    </p>

    <div class="residency-content">
      <div class="residency-block">
        <h3>Investor Residence Permit</h3>
        <p>
          Brazil offers an investor residence permit pathway that can include
          real estate investment. The commonly cited thresholds are:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>R$1,000,000</strong> for general investment</li>
          <li><strong>R$700,000</strong> for investments in the North and Northeast regions</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Florianopolis is in the South region, so the general threshold typically applies.
          Rules and requirements change. This is orientation, not guidance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="residency-block">
        <h3>Other Visa Options</h3>
        <p>
          Brazil has various visa categories including digital nomad visas, retirement
          visas, and family reunification pathways. Each has different requirements
          and benefits. The right path depends on your situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="residency-block">
        <h3>Path to Citizenship</h3>
        <p>
          Permanent residents can apply for Brazilian citizenship after meeting
          residency requirements (typically four years of continuous residence,
          with some exceptions). Brazilian citizenship includes visa-free access
          to many countries and the right to live and work in Brazil indefinitely.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="residency-disclaimer">
      <p>
        <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This is not legal advice. Immigration rules
        change frequently. Requirements vary based on nationality and personal
        circumstances. Verify all information with a qualified Brazilian
        immigration attorney before making any decisions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

